Resolution of primary HCV infections is associated with the vigorous responses of HLA class I-restricted (CD8+) and class II- restricted (CD4+) T cells to multiple epitopes derived from both structural and non-structural proteins.14Although such broad- based responses are readily detected early during the course of infection regardless of clinical outcome, they are not maintained in patients who develop chronic disease.15Thus, while individuals who spontaneously clear infection continue to exhibit a proliferative response to a wide range of class I- and class II- restricted epitopes, chronically infected patients respond to a limited number only.16A variety of factors purportedly contribute to the diminished T cell responses observed in chronically infected patients including: viral mutation and escape linked to both CD4 and CD8 T cell failure, CD4 T cell anergy, CD8 T cell exhaustion, induction of FoxP3+regulatory T (reg) cells and/or impaired dendritic cell function.17-26*Correspondence to: Stephen H.
